llingstone Castle, Kent, England":"Lullingstone, Kent, England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Church of St Mary Woolnoth, City of London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Lullingstone Castle, Eynsford, Kent, England":"Eynsford, Kent, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1363–21 March 1409":"1363–21 maart 1409","1363–1409":"1363–1409","1365–1446":"1365–1446","1358–1412":"1358–1412","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1389–1439":"1389–1439","1338–1410":"1338–1410","1363":"1363","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","22 February 1389":"22 februari 1389","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1358":"1358","1446":"1446","1412":"1412","1389":"1389","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1409":"1409","about 1372":"circa 1372","21 March 1409":"21 maart 1409","1439":"1439","Lullingstone Castle, Kent, England":"Lullingstone, Kent, England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Church of St Mary Woolnoth, City of London, England":"London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lullingstone Castle, Eynsford, Kent, England":"Eynsford, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1363–21 March 1409":"1363–21 March 1409","1363–1409":"1363–1409","1365–1446":"1365–1446","1358–1412":"1358–1412","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1389–1439":"1389–1439","1338–1410":"1338–1410","1363":"1363","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","22 February 1389":"22 February 1389","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1358":"1358","1446":"1446","1412":"1412","1389":"1389","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1409":"1409","about 1372":"about 1372","21 March 1409":"21 March 1409","1439":"1439","Lullingstone Castle, Kent, England":"Lullingstone, Kent, England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Church of St Mary Woolnoth, City of London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Lullingstone Castle, Eynsford, Kent, England":"Eynsford, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hadley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands): habitational name from either of three places called Hadley, in Worcestershire and Shropshire, or from either of two places called Hadleigh, in Essex and Suffolk, or Monken Hadley in Middlesex. The first is named from the Old English personal name <i>Hadda</i> + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, (woodland) clearing’; the others are from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heathland, heather’ + <i>lēah</i>.","In some cases also Native American (Navajo): variant of   Hatathlie   ‘singer (i.e. medicine man)’. Compare   Singer   5."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatathlie","meanings":["Native American (Navajo): from an American English altered (and shortened) form of a Navajo personal name such as <i>Hataałii Yázhí</i>, based on the occupational name <i>hataałii</i> which means literally ‘singer’ and denotes a medicine man. Compare   Hadley   2 and   Singer   6."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":19,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Hadley was born in 1363 as the daughter of John Hadley. She married William de Pêche in 1380, in Eynsford, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 21 March 1409, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 46, and was buried in London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1363–21 March 1409":"1363–21. märts 1409","1363–1409":"1363–1409","1365–1446":"1365–1446","1358–1412":"1358–1412","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1389–1439":"1389–1439","1338–1410":"1338–1410","1363":"1363","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","22 February 1389":"22. veebruar 1389","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1358":"1358","1446":"1446","1412":"1412","1389":"1389","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1409":"1409","about 1372":"umbes 1372","21 March 1409":"21. märts 1409","1439":"1439","Lullingstone Castle, Kent, England":"Lullingstone, Kent, England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Church of St Mary Woolnoth